      <body>
         <entry xml:id="agba-bastes-dlgenr"
                xml:lang="en"
                type="mainEntry"
                prev="#avli-dlgenr"
                next="#agbastos-dlgenr"
                source="Genesis Rabbah">
            <form type="lemma" opt="false">
               <orth type="lemma" xml:lang="jpa" opt="false" select="true">אגבה בסטס</orth>
               <orth type="transliteration" xml:lang="fjb" opt="false">ʾgbh bsṭs</orth>
               <pron notation="rabbinic" opt="false">agbah basṭes</pron>
               <gramGrp opt="false">
                  <gram type="pos" opt="false">noun</gram>
                  <gram type="gen" opt="false">m</gram>
               </gramGrp>
            </form>
            <sense xml:id="agba-bastes-dlgenr-1" opt="false">
               <usg type="domain" opt="false">administration</usg>
               <usg type="socioCultural" norm="borrowing" opt="false">cultural borrowing</usg>
               <usg type="normativity" opt="false">standard</usg>
               <usg type="meaningType" opt="false">lit.</usg>
               <usg type="frequency" opt="false">hapax legomenon</usg>
               <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en" subtype="sense">
                  <quote>executor, collector of debts, apparitor</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="translationEquivalent" xml:lang="grc">
                  <usg opt="false">
                     <lang opt="false">Post Classical Greek+</lang>
                  </usg>
                  <quote>ἐκβιβαστής</quote>
               </cit>
               <cit type="example">
<!-- here we have a passage with various readings. Manuscript sigla are provided in the @wit attribute. We have to look how well mixed content works with RTL scripts. -->
                  <quote xml:lang="jpa">
                     <app>
                        <lem>אגבה בסטס</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#Ox1">אגבבסמוס</rdg>
                        <rdg wit="#Ox2">אגבבסמוס</rdg>
                     </app>
             במדינה
         </quote>
                  <bibl default="false" status="draft">
                     <ref type="witness">8,1</ref>
                     <ref type="witness">I 55:3</ref>
                  </bibl>
                  <cit type="translation">
<!-- The english translation of the passage is encoded in a nested cit element -->
                     <quote xml:lang="en">
"the executor in his province”
<!-- The english translation of the passage-->
            </quote>
                  </cit>
               </cit>
            </sense>
            <etym type="borrowing" opt="false">
               <lbl opt="false">source language</lbl>
               <lang opt="false">Post Classical Greek+</lang>
               <cit type="etymon" xml:lang="grc">
                  <xr type="related" opt="false">
                     <lbl opt="false">Cf. LSJ</lbl>
                     <ref target="http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/morph?l=e%29kbi%5Eb-asth%2Fs&amp;la=greek&amp;can=e%29kbi%5Eb-asth%2Fs0"
                          type="entry">ἐκβιβαστής</ref>
                  </xr>
               </cit>
            </etym>
            <note anchored="true">
Sperber 1984:31 suggests also ~Gr. <term xml:lang="grc">ἐκβιαστής</term> 
“exactor” (Sophocles 431b). 
Aquila in Dtn 16,18 renders <term xml:lang="grc">έκβιβαστάς</term> for <term xml:lang="jpa">שטרים</term> 
but <term xml:lang="grc">έκβιαστήν</term>, <term xml:lang="grc">ἐκβιαστής</term> 
for <term xml:lang="jpa">שטר</term> in Prov. 6,8. In our context the meaning 
executor ~ Gr. <term xml:lang="grc">ἐκβιβαστής</term> is however more suitable, cf. 
      <ref type="entry" xml:lang="jpa">בייא</ref>
            </note>
